# {{biochemistry}} the [[base]] of a [[nucleic acid]] in either [[RNA]] or [[DNA]]. These [[base]]s include [[cytosine]], [[guanine]], [[adenine]], [[thymine]] (in [[DNA]]) and [[uracil]] (in [[RNA]]). They are abbreviated as [[C]], [[G]], [[A]], [[T]], and [[U]], respectively. Nucleobases may pair [[non-cavalent]]ly (or [[hydrogen bond]]) with a [[complementary]] [[base]] of another [[nucleic acid]] in a process called "[[base pair]]ing").

